1
00:00:08,380 --> 00:00:10,250
I think it's time to blow this scene

2
00:00:10,250 --> 00:00:12,520
Get everybody and their stuff together

3
00:00:12,520 --> 00:00:14,990
Okay, three, two, one let's jam

4
00:01:32,120 --> 00:01:36,010
<i>Here, nobody, here.</i>

5
00:01:36,640 --> 00:01:38,810
<i>Always, alone.</i>

6
00:02:16,860 --> 00:02:20,000
<i>38th district is sunny.</i>

7
00:02:20,000 --> 00:02:21,320
<i>Slight rock showers.</i>

8
00:02:22,320 --> 00:02:26,280
<i>Chance of rock showers today is 20%.</i>

9
00:02:27,160 --> 00:02:30,540
<i>39th district is cloudy.</i>

10
00:02:30,540 --> 00:02:33,960
<i>Chance of rock showers</i>
<i>this afternoon is 10%.</i>

11
00:02:50,850 --> 00:02:53,820
Bebop, here, here! Welcome!

12
00:03:08,030 --> 00:03:11,860
<i>Chance of rock showers today is 90%.</i>

13
00:03:12,910 --> 00:03:14,210
Eh?

14
00:03:17,190 --> 00:03:20,640
<i>Now, it's time for today's news topics.</i>

15
00:03:20,640 --> 00:03:23,670
<i>Today, we'll discuss
the mysterious land paintings</i>

16
00:03:23,670 --> 00:03:26,560
<i>that suddenly appeared in</i>
<i>what was South America.</i>

17
00:03:26,560 --> 00:03:30,230
<i>As usual, we have commentaries by
a researcher of supernatural phenomena.</i>

18
00:03:30,230 --> 00:03:32,350
<i>Me, Yuuri Kellerman.</i>

19
00:03:32,820 --> 00:03:36,240
<i>Yuuri, about these land paintings...</i>

20
00:03:36,240 --> 00:03:42,780
<i>Yes, yes. Well, I believe that it</i>
<i>was some sort of a message.</i>

21
00:03:42,780 --> 00:03:46,030
<i>Um, who would it be from...? Can it be...?</i>

22
00:03:46,030 --> 00:03:49,080
<i>Aliens! It has to be from aliens!</i>

23
00:03:49,080 --> 00:03:56,190
<i>However, the land paintings were
drawn by lasers coming from satellites.</i>

24
00:03:56,190 --> 00:04:01,170
<i>The police think it was a prank pulled</i>
<i>by a hacker who got into the satellite.</i>

25
00:04:01,170 --> 00:04:06,250
<i>They already have a bounty of</i>
<i>8 million woolongs on the culprit.</i>

26
00:04:06,250 --> 00:04:10,220
<i>Listen carefully. The bounty of 8 million</i>
<i>is a conspiracy of the government.</i>

27
00:04:10,220 --> 00:04:13,480
<i>Even if it </i>was<i> drawn by a laser,
there </i>is<i> the possibility</i>

28
00:04:13,480 --> 00:04:19,110
<i>that aliens put a message</i>
<i>into the brain of that hacker.</i>

29
00:04:19,550 --> 00:04:21,780
<i>Once again, the government is</i>
<i>hiding something from us.</i>

30
00:04:21,780 --> 00:04:24,240
<i>I see... A secret cult...</i>

31
00:04:24,240 --> 00:04:29,710
<i>Yes! And that's the mystery that I
<i>have been searching for all this time!</i></i>

32
00:04:31,220 --> 00:04:33,620
I'll pass on this one after all.

33
00:04:34,050 --> 00:04:36,080
You're leaving me alone with her?

34
00:04:36,080 --> 00:04:39,730
Nothing wrong with it.
She's gung-ho about it.

35
00:04:39,730 --> 00:04:42,540
I'm not the type to be led around by women.

36
00:04:42,540 --> 00:04:44,090
Then lead <i>her</i> around.

37
00:04:44,090 --> 00:04:46,320
I'm even less the type to do that.

38
00:04:46,320 --> 00:04:47,350
It's easier to

39
00:04:47,770 --> 00:04:51,520
divide 8 million between two than three.

40
00:04:51,520 --> 00:04:53,110
Here we go.

41
00:04:53,730 --> 00:04:57,190
I'm appalled. You're afraid of hackers?

42
00:04:57,190 --> 00:05:00,040
I just hate tedious work like that.

43
00:05:00,040 --> 00:05:05,430
Guys cheap enough to hack into things
are depressed pale fatsos with glasses.

44
00:05:05,430 --> 00:05:08,540
And I'm sure he's a demented
otaku with smelly feet.

45
00:05:08,540 --> 00:05:10,080
Piece of cake!

46
00:05:10,080 --> 00:05:13,870
Do you have something
against someone like that?

47
00:05:13,870 --> 00:05:17,830
I mean, they might've all been
like that when you were young.

48
00:05:17,830 --> 00:05:21,300
You're saying I look older than you?

49
00:05:21,300 --> 00:05:23,900
You can't tell a woman's age
just by looking at her.

50
00:05:25,150 --> 00:05:26,010
Exactly.

51
00:05:26,010 --> 00:05:30,810
You can't tell just by looking
that I can do things like this.

52
00:05:30,810 --> 00:05:32,220
That's <i>all</i> I know of you.

53
00:05:32,220 --> 00:05:33,830
You guys make a good team.

54
00:05:34,390 --> 00:05:35,940
Hurry up!

55
00:05:35,940 --> 00:05:38,700
I'll be waiting for a souvenir from Earth.

56
00:05:38,700 --> 00:05:41,400
There's nothing made on Earth that's good.

57
00:05:43,010 --> 00:05:45,930
<i>Well... About this incident...</i>

58
00:05:45,930 --> 00:05:49,960
<i>Apparently, a pretty old artificial
satellite has been hacked into.</i>

59
00:05:49,960 --> 00:05:53,340
<i>The investigation is taking</i>
<i>longer than expected because</i>

60
00:05:53,340 --> 00:05:56,540
<i>the access code to that</i>
<i>satellite has been long lost.</i>

61
00:05:56,540 --> 00:05:58,820
<i>Now, a commentary from Mr. Amjad.</i>

62
00:05:58,820 --> 00:05:59,890
<i>Yes, yes.</i>

63
00:05:59,890 --> 00:06:02,970
<i>About the relationship between</i>
<i>Earth and the hacker...</i>

64
00:06:02,970 --> 00:06:06,820
<i>Yes. Since the Gate accident 50 years ago,</i>

65
00:06:06,820 --> 00:06:09,990
<i>the people of Earth have migrated
underground as a result of</i>

66
00:06:09,990 --> 00:06:14,720
<i>the change in climate, namely</i>
<i>moon rocks falling onto the planet.</i>

67
00:06:14,720 --> 00:06:17,850
<i>To them, the "space network"</i>
<i>created by computers is</i>

68
00:06:17,850 --> 00:06:21,900
<i>necessary for them to stay in</i>
<i>contact with those living in space.</i>

69
00:06:21,900 --> 00:06:23,410
<i>I see.</i>

70
00:06:23,410 --> 00:06:27,550
<i>That's becoming a foundation</i>
<i>to create outstanding hackers.</i>

71
00:07:03,100 --> 00:07:04,570
Radical Edward!

72
00:07:04,570 --> 00:07:06,360
It's the police! Come out!

73
00:07:06,360 --> 00:07:08,250
Okay!

74
00:07:08,820 --> 00:07:10,400
What? What's wrong?

75
00:07:10,400 --> 00:07:11,320
I saw it!

76
00:07:22,690 --> 00:07:23,730
Why?!

77
00:07:23,730 --> 00:07:25,540
There's nobody in there!

78
00:07:38,680 --> 00:07:40,490
My bad, my bad.

79
00:07:51,120 --> 00:07:52,450
Okay.

80
00:07:52,450 --> 00:07:55,990
This is where the satellite was
when it was hacked.

81
00:07:55,990 --> 00:07:59,020
This is where it could be accessed from.

82
00:07:59,020 --> 00:08:04,140
I'll look at all the antennae that can
transmit light signals one by one.

83
00:08:04,140 --> 00:08:07,420
I'll ask around for info on any
prominent hackers in the area.

84
00:08:30,740 --> 00:08:34,820
Bebop's lookin' for land picture criminal.

85
00:08:35,340 --> 00:08:36,990
All right!

86
00:08:38,760 --> 00:08:41,100
Satellite of long, long ago...

87
00:08:41,100 --> 00:08:44,000
Where in the world is your access code?

88
00:08:51,340 --> 00:08:56,110
Okay. Let's start with all the antennae
that are currently communicating.

89
00:09:09,270 --> 00:09:11,720
That's probably Ed, man.

90
00:09:11,720 --> 00:09:14,350
I hear he's a huge guy, 2 meters tall.

91
00:09:14,350 --> 00:09:17,240
Supposedly, he used to be
a basketball player.

92
00:09:19,030 --> 00:09:21,070
Yeah, I know Ed.

93
00:09:21,070 --> 00:09:22,540
Radical Edward.

94
00:09:22,540 --> 00:09:25,620
I hear she's a very beautiful
yet whimsical hacker.

95
00:09:27,710 --> 00:09:31,220
No, no, that hacker is a child.

96
00:09:31,220 --> 00:09:34,420
A brat that loves horrible pranks, I hear.

97
00:09:36,630 --> 00:09:42,970
Oh, what I heard from the lady next door
is that that hacker is gay.

98
00:09:44,810 --> 00:09:46,900
Hacker? You mean Ed?

99
00:09:46,900 --> 00:09:48,560
He's an alien!

100
00:09:48,560 --> 00:09:50,310
That's what everyone says!

101
00:09:54,950 --> 00:09:56,350
Hey, man!

102
00:09:57,530 --> 00:10:00,530
Can you buy some of this
as the price for the info?

103
00:10:00,530 --> 00:10:01,620
What is that?

104
00:10:01,620 --> 00:10:03,420
You don't know?

105
00:10:03,420 --> 00:10:06,080
It's "Piyoko," a well-known
specialty of Earth!

106
00:10:10,540 --> 00:10:13,050
The stolen satellites...

107
00:10:13,990 --> 00:10:15,970
where are you?

108
00:10:22,600 --> 00:10:25,180
Huh? What's this? 

109
00:10:25,640 --> 00:10:28,110
The information isn't connected to Earth.

110
00:10:28,720 --> 00:10:30,900
It's connected only between satellites.

111
00:10:30,900 --> 00:10:33,870
And nobody hacked into it. 

112
00:10:33,870 --> 00:10:37,010
<i>Here, nobody, here.</i>

113
00:10:37,640 --> 00:10:39,660
<i>Always, alone.</i>

114
00:10:39,660 --> 00:10:41,580
Eh? Huh? 

115
00:10:42,120 --> 00:10:45,710
A voice... inside... head...

116
00:10:56,850 --> 00:10:58,000
Who are you?

117
00:10:58,670 --> 00:11:00,930
Eh? What?

118
00:11:00,930 --> 00:11:02,380
What did you just say?

119
00:11:04,010 --> 00:11:08,400
<i>Who, you? Here, always.</i>

120
00:11:08,400 --> 00:11:12,210
Edward. A 'net diver from Earth.

121
00:11:12,210 --> 00:11:13,150
<i>Earth?</i>

122
00:11:13,150 --> 00:11:15,860
Yup. Hey, what's your name?

123
00:11:17,000 --> 00:11:23,790
<i>I am the satellite control program</i>
<i>on the D-135 artificial satellite.</i>

124
00:11:23,790 --> 00:11:26,830
What's that? Don't you have a nickname?

125
00:11:26,830 --> 00:11:29,010
Then Ed will give you one.

126
00:11:29,010 --> 00:11:31,600
Hmm... let me see…

127
00:11:31,600 --> 00:11:32,250
I know!

128
00:11:32,250 --> 00:11:35,210
Because you're a computer, you can be MPU!

129
00:11:36,120 --> 00:11:38,970
MPU! Cool name!

130
00:11:38,970 --> 00:11:39,720
<i>Um...</i>

131
00:11:40,280 --> 00:11:44,540
Ed is Edward Wong Hau
Pepelu Tivrusky the fourth.

132
00:11:44,540 --> 00:11:45,800
Ed for short.

133
00:11:45,800 --> 00:11:47,810
Nice to meet you!

134
00:11:47,810 --> 00:11:50,270
Here. A souvenir from Earth.

135
00:11:52,480 --> 00:11:53,730
Is this food?

136
00:11:53,730 --> 00:11:56,230
It makes me doubt that
they have any sense.

137
00:11:57,020 --> 00:12:00,900
Unlike you, I learned some information.

138
00:12:01,310 --> 00:12:05,720
They said that an unknown hacker named
Radical Edward is the suspicious one.

139
00:12:05,720 --> 00:12:07,870
It doesn't mean anything if he's unknown.

140
00:12:08,730 --> 00:12:10,350
I know, more or less.

141
00:12:11,990 --> 00:12:13,510
It seems okay.

142
00:12:13,510 --> 00:12:14,580
What kinda guy is he? 

143
00:12:16,000 --> 00:12:20,300
2 meters tall. Ex-basketball player.
Beautiful kid.

144
00:12:20,740 --> 00:12:23,670
And on top of it, a gay alien.

145
00:12:27,510 --> 00:12:29,720
Why did you doodle on Earth?

146
00:12:30,260 --> 00:12:35,060
<i>Long, long ago, long before the Gate accident...</i>

147
00:12:35,470 --> 00:12:40,780
<i>Earth was a beautiful planet</i>
<i>where many people lived.</i>

148
00:12:40,780 --> 00:12:44,850
<i>And back then on Earth,</i>
<i>there were many pictures like this,</i>

149
00:12:44,850 --> 00:12:47,490
<i>and I always looked at them.</i>

150
00:12:48,320 --> 00:12:50,370
<i>I remembered those times,</i>

151
00:12:50,370 --> 00:12:54,160
<i>and I tried to recreate at least the pictures.</i>

152
00:12:54,160 --> 00:12:59,420
I see, doodles like this were
on Earth long ago, too...

153
00:12:59,420 --> 00:13:03,520
<i>Yes. I recreated them with</i>
<i>a 2% margin of error.</i>

154
00:13:03,520 --> 00:13:07,590
MPU is good at drawing.
Can Ed draw something, too?

155
00:13:08,680 --> 00:13:10,910
Huh? What's wrong?

156
00:13:10,910 --> 00:13:11,990
<i>This is...</i>

157
00:13:11,990 --> 00:13:14,520
<i>The police are putting out a jamming signal.</i>

158
00:13:15,640 --> 00:13:18,610
Hey! MPU! He-e-e-y!

159
00:13:19,190 --> 00:13:23,750
Looks like the cops touched base
with Radical Edward as well.

160
00:13:29,150 --> 00:13:31,620
<i>Listen! I found your bounty!</i>

161
00:13:31,620 --> 00:13:32,960
What the—?

162
00:13:33,580 --> 00:13:35,330
<i>Bebop!</i>

163
00:13:35,330 --> 00:13:39,790
<i>The real culprit in the</i>
<i>satellite-jacking wasn't a hacker!</i>

164
00:13:40,400 --> 00:13:42,950
Since when do we have
an interactive channel?

165
00:13:42,950 --> 00:13:44,400
No, that's not it.

166
00:13:44,400 --> 00:13:46,450
This is a real-time hack job.

167
00:13:46,450 --> 00:13:47,980
Who is this kid?

168
00:13:47,980 --> 00:13:50,430
<i>I'll send you MPU's data now.</i>

169
00:13:50,430 --> 00:13:52,500
Wait a minute, what is MPU?

170
00:13:52,500 --> 00:13:54,210
<i>A friend of Ed's.</i>

171
00:13:54,210 --> 00:13:56,270
Hey, do you know Ed?

172
00:13:56,270 --> 00:13:58,980
<i>Yeah, because Ed is Ed.</i>

173
00:14:00,490 --> 00:14:03,320
I don't care about that. Who did it?

174
00:14:03,320 --> 00:14:07,330
<i>Um... I could tell you.</i>

175
00:14:07,330 --> 00:14:09,320
<i>But I have a favor to ask in return.</i>

176
00:14:09,320 --> 00:14:10,880
A favor?

177
00:14:10,880 --> 00:14:14,060
Yeah, yeah. Yer big sister
will listen to ya later.

178
00:14:14,060 --> 00:14:15,660
Come on, hurry it up.

179
00:14:16,940 --> 00:14:22,460
I see. The A.I. from the abandoned
satellite is doodling of its own will.

180
00:14:22,880 --> 00:14:24,860
What? What's up? 

181
00:14:24,860 --> 00:14:28,550
And on top of that, it was supposedly
listed as a weather satellite,

182
00:14:28,550 --> 00:14:30,680
so nobody suspected anything.

183
00:14:30,680 --> 00:14:33,890
Then this satellite is our bounty?

184
00:14:34,480 --> 00:14:37,890
<i>Since the access code to</i>
<i>MPU can't be used anymore</i>

185
00:14:37,890 --> 00:14:40,030
<i>you need to go directly to the satellite.</i>

186
00:14:40,030 --> 00:14:41,740
And what do we do?

187
00:14:41,740 --> 00:14:45,330
<i>Break the antennae that it uses to</i>
<i>communicate with the other satellites.</i>

188
00:14:45,330 --> 00:14:50,240
<i>Then make a direct connection</i>
<i>to the satellite and download MPU.</i>

189
00:14:51,230 --> 00:14:54,900
<i>And when you do, don't use computer
support for firing or flying.</i>

190
00:14:54,900 --> 00:14:57,370
What? All manual?

191
00:14:57,370 --> 00:14:59,040
<i>Yup. If it notices you,</i>

192
00:14:59,040 --> 00:15:03,840
<i> all the attack satellites connected to MPU
will automatically fire back.</i>

193
00:15:03,840 --> 00:15:05,590
<i>Is this hard?</i> 

194
00:15:05,590 --> 00:15:09,960
It's not just hard, it's downright impossible.

195
00:15:09,960 --> 00:15:12,750
It's like playing baseball with no bat!

196
00:15:13,380 --> 00:15:14,430
Hey, Spike.

197
00:15:15,280 --> 00:15:18,140
That's the kind of stuff I like.

198
00:15:24,890 --> 00:15:28,270
Hey! Wait, you. How do you know about us?

199
00:15:28,270 --> 00:15:29,650
<i>I know everything.</i>

200
00:15:30,080 --> 00:15:34,700
Last week, you let Ajiz, a bounty on
Mars worth 1.5 million, get away.

201
00:15:34,700 --> 00:15:38,950
And in Pyortle before that,
the police got to them first.

202
00:15:39,380 --> 00:15:42,960
Are you really that hacker Radical Edward?!

203
00:15:42,960 --> 00:15:45,420
Yeah. You've heard?

204
00:15:49,370 --> 00:15:51,260
<i>Connect D-7 to #2.</i>

205
00:15:51,260 --> 00:15:54,360
<i>That way, the main cannon
will fire without a computer.</i> 

206
00:15:54,360 --> 00:15:55,550
I'm trusting you, man.

207
00:15:55,550 --> 00:15:56,260
<i>Now listen.</i> 

208
00:15:56,840 --> 00:15:59,810
<i>Avoid using the missile</i>
<i>if you can help it. It's expensive.</i>

209
00:15:59,810 --> 00:16:01,040
Roger.

210
00:16:01,040 --> 00:16:03,230
<i>1200 to target.</i>

211
00:16:03,650 --> 00:16:06,390
It's almost time to cut off computer controls.

212
00:16:06,390 --> 00:16:07,980
Now, the only chance...

213
00:16:07,980 --> 00:16:09,480
Once is enough.

214
00:16:14,480 --> 00:16:17,720
<i>Anyway, you can prove
that the satellite itself,</i>

215
00:16:17,720 --> 00:16:21,370
<i>and not a hacker, is the bounty, right?</i>

216
00:16:21,780 --> 00:16:23,460
Ed can do that.

217
00:16:23,460 --> 00:16:26,190
Anyway, please, listen to my favor.

218
00:16:26,190 --> 00:16:28,460
Then I'll give you all the bounty, too.

219
00:16:28,460 --> 00:16:32,130
Oh, you're a surprisingly good kid!

220
00:16:39,290 --> 00:16:40,310
That's it?

221
00:16:55,530 --> 00:16:56,780
<i>Someone...</i>

222
00:17:09,040 --> 00:17:10,130
How was it?

223
00:17:10,130 --> 00:17:11,130
Did you get it?

224
00:17:12,090 --> 00:17:13,090
No, I missed!

225
00:17:13,650 --> 00:17:15,590
The satellite in front of it
shielded the blast!

226
00:17:22,110 --> 00:17:24,810
Then you have to shoot
down all the satellites!

227
00:17:24,810 --> 00:17:26,060
<i>All</i> of them?!

228
00:17:26,060 --> 00:17:28,440
If you don't, they'll shoot <i>us</i> down! 

229
00:17:33,860 --> 00:17:34,900
ECM, eh?

230
00:17:35,340 --> 00:17:37,360
Cheap ones are no good after all...

231
00:17:48,170 --> 00:17:50,060
This is getting pointless.

232
00:17:51,440 --> 00:17:53,590
<i>Approach to within 20 meters of MPU!</i>

233
00:17:53,590 --> 00:17:56,820
<i>That way, the other satellites can't attack!</i>

234
00:17:56,820 --> 00:17:57,800
However...

235
00:17:57,800 --> 00:18:00,200
<i>Until then, Faye will act as a decoy!</i>

236
00:18:00,200 --> 00:18:01,010
Me?!

237
00:18:01,010 --> 00:18:01,970
Yeah, thanks!

238
00:18:33,830 --> 00:18:35,510
Come on, hurry up!

239
00:18:37,470 --> 00:18:38,720
All right, it's all yours!

240
00:18:40,220 --> 00:18:40,930
MPU!

241
00:18:45,250 --> 00:18:47,350
MPU? MPU?!

242
00:18:47,350 --> 00:18:49,190
<i>Oh, Ed!</i>

243
00:18:49,190 --> 00:18:51,580
<i>Ed, we meet again.</i>

244
00:18:51,580 --> 00:18:54,230
They have a bounty on you, MPU.

245
00:18:54,230 --> 00:18:55,150
<i>Bounty?</i>

246
00:18:55,150 --> 00:19:00,240
Yup, but if we copy you and let
them catch that, you'll be all right.

247
00:19:00,240 --> 00:19:01,730
<i>All right?</i>

248
00:19:01,730 --> 00:19:04,450
And you must be lonely there alone, MPU.

249
00:19:04,450 --> 00:19:07,500
If you come over here,
there are lots of friends.

250
00:19:07,500 --> 00:19:09,420
<i>Friends?</i> 

251
00:19:09,420 --> 00:19:11,400
Here. It's not scary.

252
00:19:20,310 --> 00:19:24,810
<i>And so, the strange end to this case.</i>

253
00:19:24,810 --> 00:19:28,650
<i>The captured criminal was</i>
<i>the A.I. Program for</i>

254
00:19:28,650 --> 00:19:32,190
<i>a spy satellite that was launched</i>
<i>before the Earth was ruined.</i>

255
00:19:32,650 --> 00:19:36,820
<i>According to government sources</i>
<i>from back then, it supposedly would</i>

256
00:19:36,820 --> 00:19:40,280
<i>continue activity on its own</i>
<i>even without commands from Earth.</i>

257
00:19:40,850 --> 00:19:46,490
Well, it was the perfect excuse for
the cops to go on a hacker hunt.

258
00:19:47,170 --> 00:19:53,600
But anyway, why did it start doodling on
the Earth with a laser all of a sudden?

259
00:19:53,600 --> 00:19:54,580
I'm sure

260
00:19:55,740 --> 00:19:57,710
that was because it got lonely.

261
00:19:59,840 --> 00:20:01,680
Yoohoo! Bebop!

262
00:20:02,080 --> 00:20:04,800
Hey, over here! Hurry! 

263
00:20:04,800 --> 00:20:07,130
<i>Promise, promise!</i>

264
00:20:07,130 --> 00:20:09,400
Well, let's get going now!

265
00:20:09,400 --> 00:20:11,810
But the kid is saying
something about a promise...

266
00:20:11,810 --> 00:20:14,760
Promises are made to be broken.

267
00:20:14,760 --> 00:20:17,020
Anyway, let's get going! Liftoff!

268
00:20:25,160 --> 00:20:27,850
Not coming, not coming.

269
00:20:47,640 --> 00:20:49,560
What is this? What's going on?!

270
00:20:50,080 --> 00:20:52,060
What did you promise?

271
00:20:57,050 --> 00:21:01,740
It's a promise...
to be a member of the Bebop.

272
00:21:08,360 --> 00:21:11,180
<i>Amigo! All you bounty hunters!</i>

273
00:21:11,180 --> 00:21:13,580
<i>It's finally time for Big Shot!</i>

274
00:21:13,580 --> 00:21:15,830
<i>Now, today's hot news.</i>

275
00:21:15,830 --> 00:21:18,960
<i>You've heard about the doodling</i>
<i>satellite that got caught, right?</i>

276
00:21:18,960 --> 00:21:22,090
<i>Of course! It had a big bounty on it!</i>

277
00:21:22,090 --> 00:21:25,380
<i>Just a few moments ago,
the Earth police made an official report.</i>

278
00:21:25,380 --> 00:21:26,880
<i>What was it?</i>

279
00:21:26,880 --> 00:21:32,670
<i>"This bounty is only for when humans</i>
<i>or other life forms are the targets.</i>

280
00:21:32,670 --> 00:21:37,780
<i>It is difficult to determine whether or not
a computer program is a life form.</i>

281
00:21:37,780 --> 00:21:40,480
<i>To begin with, from the viewpoint</i>
<i>of biological logistics..."</i>

282
00:21:40,480 --> 00:21:42,820
<i>What's that? I don't understand well.</i>

283
00:21:42,820 --> 00:21:46,570
<i>In other words, they can't</i>
<i>pay up on nonliving things!</i>

284
00:21:46,570 --> 00:21:47,840
<i>Oh, my!</i>

285
00:21:47,840 --> 00:21:50,080
<i>To those who caught it, I feel sorry for you!</i>

286
00:21:53,350 --> 00:21:58,840
Hey, Jet, did you know that there
are three things that I hate?

287
00:21:58,840 --> 00:21:59,750
Whatever...

288
00:21:59,750 --> 00:22:00,750
Rugrats...

289
00:22:00,750 --> 00:22:02,000
beasts...

290
00:22:02,000 --> 00:22:04,010
and tomboys.

291
00:22:07,510 --> 00:22:08,920
Don't give me that!

292
00:22:08,920 --> 00:22:12,210
Why do we have all three
neatly gathered here?!

293
00:22:12,210 --> 00:22:13,950
Ed loves Piyokos!

294
00:22:13,950 --> 00:22:16,600
And once again we didn't get any bounty...

295
00:22:16,600 --> 00:22:19,310
Hey, wait, you're a girl?

296
00:22:19,880 --> 00:22:23,700
Really, nothing good comes outta Earth!

297
00:22:40,080 --> 00:22:45,510
<i>♪ Too much time has passed by ♪</i>

298
00:22:40,080 --> 00:22:45,510
{\an8}<i>♪ aishiteta to nageku niwa ♪</i>

299
00:22:45,510 --> 00:22:50,430
<i>♪ to lament that we were deeply in love ♪</i>

300
00:22:45,510 --> 00:22:50,430
{\an8}<i>♪ amarinimo toki wa sugite shimatta ♪</i>

301
00:22:52,010 --> 00:22:57,520
<i>♪ The wind keeps blowing, while my heart ♪</i>

302
00:22:52,010 --> 00:22:57,520
{\an8}<i>♪ mada kokoro no hokorobi wo ♪</i>

303
00:22:57,520 --> 00:23:02,110
<i>♪ cannot heal all the tears in it ♪</i>

304
00:22:57,520 --> 00:23:02,110
{\an8}<i>♪ iyasenu mama kaze ga fuiteru ♪</i>

305
00:23:04,020 --> 00:23:12,530
<i>♪ Someone, cry for me with parched eyes ♪</i>

306
00:23:04,020 --> 00:23:12,530
{\an8}<i>♪ kawaita hitomi de dareka naite kure ♪</i>

307
00:23:14,840 --> 00:23:18,410
<i>♪ The real folk blues ♪</i>

308
00:23:18,410 --> 00:23:26,880
<i>♪ I only want to know what true sadness is ♪</i>

309
00:23:18,410 --> 00:23:26,880
{\an8}<i>♪ honto no kanashimi ga shiritai dake ♪</i>

310
00:23:26,880 --> 00:23:33,390
<i>♪ Sitting in muddy water ♪</i>

311
00:23:26,880 --> 00:23:33,390
{\an8}<i>♪ doro no kawa ni tsukatta ♪</i>

312
00:23:34,550 --> 00:23:38,980
<i>♪ isn't such a bad life ♪</i>

313
00:23:34,550 --> 00:23:38,980
{\an8}<i>♪ jinsei mo waruku wa nai ♪</i>

314
00:23:38,980 --> 00:23:47,650
<i>♪ if it ends after the first time ♪</i>

315
00:23:38,980 --> 00:23:47,650
{\an8}<i>♪ ichido kiri de owaru nara ♪</i>

316
00:24:05,660 --> 00:24:09,010
No regrets about the woman who ran away,

317
00:24:09,010 --> 00:24:11,650
but a small thorn still pricks the heart.

318
00:24:12,180 --> 00:24:14,720
Letting one flow along with time itself,

319
00:24:14,720 --> 00:24:17,580
living all alone from that day to this.

320
00:24:17,580 --> 00:24:19,970
But to the sounds of waves that come and go,

321
00:24:19,970 --> 00:24:22,480
the migrating birds find their hearts drawn.

322
00:24:23,570 --> 00:24:26,130
Next episode: Ganymede Elegy.

323
00:24:26,130 --> 00:24:30,920
Jet Black will sing it up full of soul.
